nographic encounter, a site of a very particular and important kind of knowing. In a range of social contexts and cultural settings, contributors show how the interview is experienced and imagined as a kind of space within which personal, biographic and social cues and norms can be explored and interrogated. The interview possesses its own authenticity, therefore—true to the persons involved and true to their moment of interaction—whilst at the same time providing information on human capacities and proclivities that is generalizable beyond particular social and cultural contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aInterviewing in ethnology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Methodology.2bisacsh1 aCaplan, Pat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLopes, Ana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNiehaus, Isak, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOkely, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRapport, Nigel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRapport, Nigel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSmith, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Katherine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStaples, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStaples, James, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTrias i Valls, Àngels, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311099823840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782385905?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782385905423Coveruhttps://www.degruyte